```class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> constructRectangle(int area) {
        vector<int> result;
        int L = 1, W;
        while (L * W <= area) {
            result.push_back(L);
            W = area / L;
            L++;
        }
        result.push_back(W);
        return result;
    }
};```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(area))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We use a while loop to iterate until the product of L and W is greater than the target area. In each iteration, we add L to the result vector, update W to divide the remaining area by L, and increment L by 1. After the loop, we add the final W to the result vector. This solution has a high efficiency since it only requires a single loop and a few arithmetic operations. The time complexity is O(log(area)) because the loop terminates when the product of L and W becomes greater than the target area. The space complexity is O(1) since we only use a constant amount of space for the result vector. The energy implications are low because the algorithm does not involve any complex calculations or data structures.

